<DocPageMeta Title="The ShiftEntity model"
             Section="Concepts"
             Order="10"
             Status="DocPageStatus.Draft"
             Description="What you get for free when you inherit from the ShiftEntity base class — IDs, audit fields, soft delete, the ReloadAfterSave hook, and temporal history."
             Keywords="entity,shiftentity,base class,id,audit,soft delete,reloadaftersave,temporal,createdate,lastsavedate" />

<DocSection Title="The base class">
    <p>
        Every entity in a Shift Framework project inherits from
        <code>ShiftEntity&lt;T&gt;</code>. The pattern is always the same:
    </p>

    <DocCodeBlock Code="@(@"using ShiftSoftware.ShiftEntity.Core;

namespace MyFirstShiftApp.Data.Entities;

public class Product : ShiftEntity<Product>
{
    public string Name { get; set; } = """";
    public decimal Price { get; set; }
}")" />

    <p>
        The generic type argument <code>&lt;Product&gt;</code> is the entity itself —
        a curiously-recurring template pattern that lets the base class expose
        strongly-typed helpers without losing your concrete type. You'll see
        <code>: ShiftEntity&lt;ThisEntity&gt;</code> on every entity in the project.
    </p>

    <p>By inheriting from this base, your entity gets eight things for free:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>An auto-generated <code>long ID</code> primary key</li>
        <li><code>CreateDate</code> and <code>LastSaveDate</code> audit timestamps</li>
        <li><code>CreatedByUserID</code> and <code>LastSavedByUserID</code> audit user tracking</li>
        <li><code>IsDeleted</code> for soft-delete behavior</li>
        <li><code>LastReplicationDate</code> for the optional Cosmos DB replication pipeline</li>
        <li>The <code>ReloadAfterSave</code> hook for repositories that need fresh state after a save</li>
        <li>Compatibility with the <code>ShiftRepository</code> base class and the OData query pipeline</li>
        <li>Compatibility with the <code>IShiftEntityMapper</code> abstraction (Manual / Mapperly / Mapster / AutoMapper)</li>
    </ul>
</DocSection>

<DocSection Title="The ID convention">
    <p>
        IDs are always <code>long</code> (64-bit signed integer), always
        auto-generated by the database, and always called <code>ID</code> — never
        <code>Id</code>, never <code>ProductId</code>, never <code>Pk</code>. The
        framework leans on this convention everywhere: repositories expect
        <code>long</code> primary keys, OData filters expect a column named
        <code>ID</code>, and the JSON serializers are configured to spell it
        <code>"ID"</code> on the wire.
    </p>

    <DocCallout Type="DocCalloutType.Note">
        If you're migrating an existing database with <code>Guid</code> or
        composite keys, Shift Framework will fight you. The opinionated
        <code>long ID</code> convention is foundational and not easily swapped.
        Greenfield projects almost always benefit from the convention; brownfield
        projects with established schemas typically need a translation layer at
        the boundary.
    </DocCallout>
</DocSection>

<DocSection Title="Audit fields">
    <p>The four audit fields are:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><code>CreateDate</code> — when the row was first inserted. Set once, never changed.</li>
        <li><code>LastSaveDate</code> — when the row was last modified. Updated on every save.</li>
        <li><code>CreatedByUserID</code> — the ShiftIdentity user who inserted the row. Set once.</li>
        <li><code>LastSavedByUserID</code> — the ShiftIdentity user who last modified the row. Updated on every save.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
        You don't set these fields yourself. <code>ShiftRepository</code> populates
        them automatically inside <code>SaveChangesAsync</code>: it inspects the
        change tracker, finds entities in <code>Added</code> and <code>Modified</code>
        states, and assigns the audit fields based on the current request's user
        and the current timestamp.
    </p>

    <p>
        This means that as long as you go through the repository (which you
        always should), audit fields are correct without you ever thinking about
        them. The only time you'll see them in your code is when you display them
        in a UI or query against them.
    </p>
</DocSection>

<DocSection Title="Soft delete">
    <p>
        <code>IsDeleted</code> is a boolean. When the repository's
        <code>DeleteAsync</code> method is called with <code>isHardDelete: false</code>
        (the default), the row isn't physically removed from the database — its
        <code>IsDeleted</code> flag is set to <code>true</code> and the row stays
        in the table.
    </p>

    <p>
        Every <code>SELECT</code> the framework issues then automatically filters
        out soft-deleted rows via an EF Core global query filter. From the
        application's perspective, the row is gone. From the database's
        perspective, it's still there, available for audit, recovery, and
        historical reporting.
    </p>

    <DocCallout Type="DocCalloutType.Tip">
        If you ever need to query soft-deleted rows directly — say, for an admin
        "deleted items" view or a recovery flow — pass
        <code>disableGlobalFilters: true</code> to the repository methods. The
        global filter is bypassed and you'll see <code>IsDeleted = true</code>
        rows again.
    </DocCallout>

    <p>
        Hard delete (<code>isHardDelete: true</code>) does exist for cases where
        you genuinely need the row gone — typically test cleanup, GDPR-compliant
        erasure, or rows that never carried meaningful audit value. Use sparingly.
    </p>
</DocSection>

<DocSection Title="The ReloadAfterSave hook">
    <p>
        Some saves need to read the database back after committing — for example,
        when an entity has computed columns, database-generated defaults, or
        navigation properties that should be eager-loaded for the response DTO.
        The framework expresses this with a single boolean on the entity:
    </p>
    <DocCodeBlock Code="@(@"public class Product : ShiftEntity<Product>
{
    public string Name { get; set; } = """";
    public long? CategoryID { get; set; }
    public Category? Category { get; set; }   // navigation property

    public override void OnSaving()
    {
        // Tell the repository: after SaveChangesAsync, reload me with my Category included.
        ReloadAfterSave = true;
    }
}")" />

    <p>
        When <code>ShiftRepository</code> sees <code>ReloadAfterSave = true</code> on
        an entity that just finished saving, it issues a fresh
        <code>SELECT</code> with whatever <code>Includes</code> the repository
        defines and returns the rehydrated entity. The View DTO mapper then sees
        the populated navigation properties and can project them into the response.
    </p>

    <p>
        <code>ReloadAfterSave</code> is marked <code>[NotMapped]</code> — it lives
        in memory only and never touches the database. It's a coordination flag
        between your entity logic and the repository, nothing more.
    </p>
</DocSection>

<DocSection Title="Temporal tables">
    <p>
        For entities where you want SQL Server's built-in temporal history
        tracking (every change to a row is automatically captured in a system-versioned
        history table), add the <code>[TemporalShiftEntity]</code> attribute:
    </p>

    <DocCodeBlock Code="@(@"using ShiftSoftware.ShiftEntity.Core;

[TemporalShiftEntity]
public class Vehicle : ShiftEntity<Vehicle>
{
    public string Make { get; set; } = """";
    public string Model { get; set; } = """";
}")" />

    <p>
        At migration time, the framework configures the table as
        <code>SYSTEM_VERSIONED</code> with a paired <code>VehicleHistory</code>
        shadow table. Every <code>INSERT</code>, <code>UPDATE</code>, and
        <code>DELETE</code> automatically writes a snapshot row to the history
        table with <code>PeriodStart</code> and <code>PeriodEnd</code> timestamps.
    </p>

    <p>
        You can then query the history of any row using the repository's
        <code>asOf</code> parameter, e.g.
        <code>FindAsync(vehicleId, asOf: DateTimeOffset.UtcNow.AddDays(-7))</code>
        to see what the row looked like a week ago.
    </p>

    <DocCallout Type="DocCalloutType.Warning">
        Temporal tables are a SQL Server feature. If you're targeting a database
        that doesn't support them (PostgreSQL, MySQL, SQLite), do not use this
        attribute — the migration will fail to apply.
    </DocCallout>
</DocSection>

<DocSection Title="The ShiftEntity contract, in one sentence">
    <p>
        <b>An entity is the canonical representation of a row in your database</b>
        — it has an identity, an audit trail, a soft-delete flag, and a coordination
        hook for the repository. Everything else (DTOs for the API, projections
        for OData, mappers, controllers, Blazor pages) is built on this single
        consistent shape.
    </p>

    <p>
        The next concept page (<MudLink Href="/concepts/dto-pattern">The DTO pattern</MudLink>)
        explains the ViewAndUpsert / List pattern that translates between the
        entity and what travels over the wire.
    </p>
</DocSection>
